\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy prevents the unauthorized disclosure of Confidential and Restricted data,
 including Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 by enforcing strict lifecycle constraints from media provisioning through destruction,
 consistent with FBI CJIS Security Policy v6.0 and NIST SP 800-88 Rev.
 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Media Access and Storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County Personnel shall store physical and digital media containing Confidential or Restricted information (including CJI) within physically secure locations or locked containers when not in active use.
 Media shall only be accessible to authorized personnel with a validated business need-to-know.
 Removable digital media shall be encrypted using cryptographic modules validated under the NIST Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) prior to storing any Level 3 (Confidential) or Level 4 (Restricted) data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Media Marking and Labeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County Personnel shall mark or label physical media and removable digital media containing Confidential or Restricted data with the assigned classification level.
 Labels shall omit system-specific or operational details that could increase the risk of targeted theft.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exception
\series default
:
 Media that cannot physically accept a label (e.g.,
 micro-form factor storage,
 firmware-embedded media) shall be marked via the associated container or inventory record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Media Transport
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County Personnel shall transport media containing Confidential or Restricted data using continuous chain-of-custody controls.
 Digital media in transit shall employ cryptographic modules validated under the NIST Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP).
 If physical media containing Restricted data (e.g.,
 printed CJI) must be transported outside of a physically secure location,
 the media shall remain under the direct,
 continuous physical control of authorized personnel or be shipped via a tracked courier service utilizing signature verification upon delivery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Digital Media Sanitization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Elko County retains drives at the end of their operational use rather than releasing them to external parties.
 Digital media removed from systems shall be retained for internal reuse subject to the classification constraints defined in this section,
 or physically destroyed.
 External release of digital media is prohibited except under the narrow fallback defined in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Prior to sanitization of media from systems scheduled for decommissioning,
 Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall confirm that audit log custody transfer under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Audit Logging and Monitoring Policy) has been completed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Media — Destruction Only
\series default
:
 Media that stores or has stored Criminal Justice Information (CJI) shall be physically destroyed.
 CJI media shall not enter the internal reuse pool and shall not be released to external parties under any circumstance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Internal Reuse — Clear
\series default
:
 Systems Administrators and Network Administrators may execute Clear on media that solely stored Level 1 (Public) or Level 2 (Internal Use) data when the media will be reused at the same or lower classification level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Internal Reuse — Purge
\series default
:
 Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall execute Purge on media that previously stored Level 3 (Confidential) or Level 4 (Restricted) non-CJI data prior to internal reuse.
 The Purge method shall be appropriate to the media architecture per NIST SP 800-88 Rev.
 1 (e.g.,
 Cryptographic Erase or firmware Block Erase for solid-state media;
 manufacturer-specified overwrite for magnetic media).
 Cryptographic Erase constitutes an acceptable Purge method only where the storage device natively supports it and employs cryptographic modules validated under the NIST Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Destroy
\series default
:
 Mandatory for End-of-Life (EOL) digital media and for any media that cannot be successfully purged.
 Destruction shall render the data permanently irretrievable and the media physically unusable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fallback — External Release Without Drive Retention
\series default
:
 Where operational circumstances preclude drive retention (e.g.,
 pre-existing vendor leases lacking a "Keep Your Drive" provision under Section 6.8),
 Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall execute Purge on-site using a vendor-provided factory overwrite utility or equivalent method appropriate to the media architecture per NIST SP 800-88 Rev.
 1 before the drive leaves County custody.
 This fallback shall not apply to CJI media;
 CJI drives shall be removed and destroyed prior to asset return regardless of any contractual provision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Networking Equipment
\series default
:
 Network Administrators shall sanitize networking equipment non-volatile memory using vendor-approved factory-reset commands or physical destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Equipment Testing
\series default
:
 Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall test sanitization equipment and procedures annually to verify that the intended sanitization is achieved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exception — Legal Hold
\series default
:
 Assets subject to an active legal hold,
 public records preservation requirement,
 audit,
 or incident investigation shall not proceed to sanitization until the hold is formally released,
 consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Physical Media Sanitization and Destruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County Personnel shall destroy physical media (e.g.,
 paper documents) containing Confidential or Restricted data when no longer required,
 executing a method that renders the information unrecoverable (e.g.,
 cross-cut shredding or incineration).
 The destruction of physical media containing Personally Identifiable Information (PII) shall comply with the destruction standards mandated by NRS 603A.210.
 All County Personnel shall not place intact physical media containing sensitive data into standard waste or recycling receptacles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Records of Sanitization,
 Disposal,
 and Verification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall comprehensively document and verify all sanitization and disposal actions for IT-managed assets.
 Required documentation shall include the date of sanitization,
 the unique Asset Identifier (Tag ID),
 the specific sanitization method utilized,
 the final disposition of the media,
 the identity of the personnel executing the sanitization,
 and the identity of the personnel performing the post-sanitization verification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For media that stores or has stored Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 the post-sanitization verification shall be performed by a secondary,
 independent Systems Administrator or Network Administrator who did not execute the initial sanitization,
 consistent with NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 MP-6(7) (Dual Authorization).
 Verification shall consist of a documented test read or visual inspection to confirm the sanitization was effective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Electronic waste (E-Waste) transferred to approved third-party recycling vendors shall be accompanied by a vendor-issued Certificate of Destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Retention
\series default
:
 Information Operations shall retain Certificates of Destruction and sanitization logs in accordance with LRDA 20070440 (Fixed Assets and Inventories).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Prohibited Media Types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County Personnel shall not connect or operate personally owned removable media (e.g.,
 personal USB flash drives,
 external hard drives) on Elko County information systems.
 All County Personnel shall use only County-procured,
 encrypted portable storage devices that are cataloged as Configuration Items under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Configuration Management (CMDB) Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Multifunction Printers (MFPs) and Copier Handling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Elko County utilizes MFPs with internal storage drives capable of caching Confidential and Restricted data.
 The terminal disposition of these assets is subject to chain-of-custody and sanitization controls.
 Systems Administrators shall document MFP models and their configuration limitations in the Configuration Management Database (CMDB) per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and in supporting Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automated Data Removal Limitations
\series default
:
 Systems Administrators shall configure MFPs to execute automated job data removal no less than weekly and shall implement automated alerting for job data removal failures.
 In the event of an automated job data removal failure,
 Systems Administrators shall execute a manual clearing within twenty-four (24) hours of the alert.
 Automated job data removal operates solely as a defense-in-depth risk mitigation and does not constitute terminal sanitization for CJI media.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Contractual "Keep Your Drive" Requirement
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall require a "Keep Your Drive" provision in all MFP lease or purchase agreements executed after the effective date of this policy.
 At lease expiration or hardware replacement,
 Systems Administrators shall remove and retain the internal storage media for destruction in accordance with the Destroy method defined in Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
On-Site Vendor Sanitization
\series default
:
 For pre-existing lease agreements executed prior to the effective date of this policy that lack a "Keep Your Drive" provision,
 Systems Administrators shall execute the External Release Without Drive Retention fallback defined in Section 6.4 on-site before removing the asset from Elko County facilities.
 Systems Administrators shall visually verify the sanitization action and obtain a Certificate of Sanitization prior to the hardware's departure.
 Where the MFP stored or may have stored CJI,
 Systems Administrators shall remove and destroy the drive per Section 6.4 regardless of the lease terms,
 and the asset shall be returned to the vendor without the drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Inoperable Media (Break/Fix)
\series default
:
 Systems Administrators shall not release inoperable MFP drives that cannot be logically overwritten to vendor technicians.
 Elko County shall classify these drives as physical media for destruction and shall retain them regardless of warranty or lease return requirements.
 The IT Director shall notify vendors of this requirement in writing prior to any service event to ensure compliance at the time of a break/fix call.
\end_layout

